(or is this en œuvres complètes?) Cf Note 2. p. 202. Derrida says he's referring to the Oeuvres Completes (Pleiade) only when the text appeared in one of the three volumes published before 1967. For other books (except the Essai sur l'Origine des langues), he's using Garnier editions. Jin: Hi, I just checked his copy of Emile and it's a Garnier edition. If he was indeed using Oevres complètes version for Emile, it would have been Tome II but we don't have that volume. This copy seems to be off in terms of page numbers because he sometimes cites pages that correspond to the introduction in this book.

CV: I only worked on the first 3 tags and looked for the pages in the edition we have. There was no annotation. However, in this edition, the Chapter 4 (and the Profession de foi in particular) is highly annotated, with a focus on the words "comparaison" or "comparer", "sens", "voix"...
